To determine if the relationship between the values of x and their corresponding y-values is nonlinear, we need to analyze the pattern of the y-values in each table.

(A) \begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|c|c|} \hline $x$ & 1 & 2 & 3 & 4 \\ \hline $y$ & 8 & 11 & 14 & 17 \\ \hline \end{tabular}

The difference between consecutive y-values is constant: 11 - 8 = 3, 14 - 11 = 3, and 17 - 14 = 3. This indicates a linear relationship.

(B) \begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|c|c|} \hline $x$ & 1 & 2 & 3 & 4 \\ \hline $y$ & 4 & 8 & 12 & 16 \\ \hline \end{tabular}

The difference between consecutive y-values is constant: 8 - 4 = 4, 12 - 8 = 4, and 16 - 12 = 4. This indicates a linear relationship.

(C) \begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|c|c|} \hline $x$ & 1 & 2 & 3 & 4 \\ \hline $y$ & 8 & 13 & 18 & 23 \\ \hline \end{tabular}

The difference between consecutive y-values is constant: 13 - 8 = 5, 18 - 13 = 5, and 23 - 18 = 5. This indicates a linear relationship.

(D) \begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|c|c|} \hline $x$ & 1 & 2 & 3 & 4 \\ \hline $y$ & 6 & 12 & 24 & 48 \\ \hline \end{tabular}

The relationship between the x and y-values is not linear. The y-values are doubling as x increases by 1. This indicates a nonlinear relationship.

The correct answer is (D) \boxed{D}.
